<p><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-43" src="http://192.145.233.214/~siddharthamukher/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/sid.jpeg" alt="sid" srcset="http://siddharthamukherjee.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/sid.jpeg 500w, http://siddharthamukherjee.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/sid-228x300.jpeg 228w" sizes="(max-width: 500px) 85vw, 500px" /></p>
<div class="coyright_photo">Photograph © Deborah Feingold</div>
</div>
<div class="sid_content col-sm-8">
<p>Siddhartha Mukherjee is the author of <a href="the-emperor-of-all-maladies"><em>The Emperor of All Maladies: A Biography of Cancer</em></a>, winner of the 2011 Pulitzer Prize in general nonfiction, and <a href="the-laws-of-medecine"><em>The Laws of Medicine</em></a>. He is the editor of Best Science Writing 2013.</p>
<p>Siddhartha Mukherjee’s <a href="the-gene-an-intimate-history"><em><strong>THE GENE: An Intimate History</strong></em></a>  is his latest work &#8211; the story of the quest to decipher the master-code of instructions that makes and defines humans, that governs our form, function, and fate and determines the future of our children.</p>
<p>Mukherjee is an assistant professor of medicine at Columbia University and a <a href="http://mukherjeelab.com/" target="_blank">cancer physician and researcher.</a> A Rhodes scholar, he graduated from Stanford University, University of Oxford, and Harvard Medical School. He has published articles in Nature, <em>The New England Journal of Medicine,</em> <em>The New York Times</em>, and <em>Cell.</em> He lives in New York with his wife and daughters.</p>
